graphicalElements.text: A mixed group of customers have arrived at the bar. They are discussing what to order. They are quite loud and become progressively louder and boisterous. You suspect they are intoxicated. How do you approach the group?
This is very friendly and you seem interested. However, with an open question you could engage customers, providing opportunities to assess sobriety.
Very direct. It sounds like you are implying there's a problem already.
A professional and friendly greeting. You are more likely to obtain relevant information with this approach and focused questions.
Serving customers you think may be intoxicated is against the law. You can't compromise.
In a firm but not authoritarian way you made the policy clear. Great job.
While this is correct, the quick, short response may seem uncaring and annoy customers unnecessarily.
Yes - This is correct! While being succinct with your explanations, be sure not to sound overly authoritative or 'threatening' with your tone.
Never refer to a drunk person as drunk! This can easily escalate their anger and they may react aggressively.
Great approach! Asking for a name and addressing that person specifically is very effective here!
Very well played! Your tone, attitude and explanations are expressed really well.
You are being professional, giving some valid explanations. Don't forget to offer safe transport solutions.
This explanation seems delivered in haste and with a threatening tone which is not effective. Here, the idea is to avoid escalations not to accelerate them!
